{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619092"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:28:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16529"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16529"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.31,0.03,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9220"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114164"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9220"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16529"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96164"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5939"},{"type":"tags","id":"6087"},{"type":"tags","id":"10274"},{"type":"tags","id":"10317"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21859"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21863"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114164"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EUpper motor neurons extend from the motor cortex to the anterior horn of the spinal cord, where they synapse with lower motor neurons. Lesions affecting these pathways produce characteristic clinical findings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is typically seen in an upper motor neuron lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clonus","Fasciculations","Decreased muscle tone","Hyporeflexia","Downgoing plantar response"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn upper motor neuron lesions, \u003Cstrong\u003Eclonus\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic finding due to loss of descending inhibitory control. This rhythmic muscle contraction occurs when a muscle is suddenly stretched and held in that position. Other typical features include hyperreflexia, positive Babinski response (upgoing plantar response), and spasticity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasciculations\u003C/strong\u003E are spontaneous muscle twitches seen in lower motor neuron disorders. \u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased muscle tone\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in lower motor neuron lesions, whereas upper motor neuron lesions cause increased tone (spasticity). \u003Cstrong\u003EHyporeflexia\u003C/strong\u003E characterises lower motor neuron lesions, whilst upper motor neuron lesions cause hyperreflexia. A \u003Cstrong\u003Edowngoing plantar response\u003C/strong\u003E is normal in adults; upper motor neuron lesions cause an upgoing plantar response (positive Babinski sign).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther features of upper motor neuron lesions include weakness in a pyramidal distribution (extensors in upper limb, flexors in lower limb), loss of fine motor control, and preserved muscle bulk due to intact lower motor neuron trophic effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Upper motor neuron lesions cause increased muscle tone, hyperreflexia, and positive Babinski (upgoing plantar) response.","Upper motor neuron lesions typically preserve muscle bulk due to intact lower motor neuron trophic effects.","The pattern of weakness in upper motor neuron lesions follows a pyramidal distribution affecting extensors in upper limbs and flexors in lower limbs."],"references":["Menon P, Vucic S. The Upper Motor Neuron-Improved Knowledge from ALS and Related Clinical Disorders. Brain Sci. 2021 Jul 21;11(8):958. doi: 10.3390/brainsci11080958. PMID: 34439577; PMCID: PMC8392624","Emos MC, Agarwal S. Neuroanatomy, Upper Motor Neuron Lesion. 2023 Aug 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725990","de Carvalho M, Swash M. Upper and lower motor neuron neurophysiology and motor control. Handb Clin Neurol. 2023;195:17-29. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-323-98818-6.00018-2. PMID: 37562869","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96164"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16529"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96164"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T11:24:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T11:24:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9220"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114164"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt